description.value: Terracotta ithyphallic figure with yoke.  A male celebrant, tending towards the grotesque, in a procession and bearing a yoke from which are suspended by ropes two sealed Egyptian amphorae, this is balanced on the man’s right by a colossal phallus, also hung from a rope. The man’s body is frontal, but he strides somewhat to his right, his head turned slightly that way, looking down. With each hand he holds the ropes of his load. Between his legs is a large hole for his own, separately made phallus, now lost, but its plaster adhesive remains. He wears a short pleated skirt with a waistband, and a knobbed pointed cap, also pleated and encircled by a fillet knotted at the front; his receding hair shows below the brim. The back is summarily treated and a suspension-lug is placed at the nape of the neck.  Hollow; two-piece mould. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt; sparse traces of an overall white dressing, painted dark pink in the area between his skirt and the amphorae.

description.value: Yellowish-white head of a female llimestone figure. Only the head, broken into many individual parts, is preserved. Particularly parts from the back and the top are missing. Smaller areas chipped; the tip of the nose is missing. The face is oval in shape with very large eyes whose outer edges are reaching far into the temples. The nose broadens towards the tip; the mouth is very broad with slim lips and smiles slightly. It is almost worked by means of a groove and the lips are hardly protruding. The chin is sturdy. The figure wears a headscarf with a diadem-like addition which is only separated from the forehead by means of a small dent. The ears are decorated with ear-caps and earrings. The back is flat.

description.value: Head of terracotta figure.  A woman’s head broken from a figure; the hair is of the melon style and is drawn back into a group of four buns at the back of the head; she wears ball earrings, the right one largely lost. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt. Traces of pink paint at the hairline over the brow; red and pink paint in the hair.

description.value: Upper part (without head) of white limestone female figure, standing, holding a bird; painted.Preserved is only the upper body without the head. Parts broken off at right upper arm; light damages. The bird's head is missing. Two drill holes near the lower break, between arm and body, go through pierce the sculpture horizongally and on both sides feature a grooved channel leading to up to the break, so as to accommodated a staple; possibly modern. Traces of paint: red rectangular collar around the breasts, red bands around the right wrist, the medallion is red; red on and around the feet of the bird. Black on the right hand and right elbow. The left arm hangs straight down while the bent right arm with the hand right below the chest holds a bird tightly. She is wearinga pearl necklace with a pendant and a neckband rendered in a fine relief and tightly fitting to the neck, which consists of four evenly distributed rows of pearls and a central medallion, from which short chains are hanging down. Each three tresses with pointed edges fall forward onto the shoulders; five tresses fall onto the back. Small oblique lines structure the tresses from the right and left side. The back is less carefully rendered.

description.value:
Fragmentary steatite figure of the god Min, the lower body and right arm now lost.

The god Min is shown with a bare chest and torso and clear outlines of the musculature across the abdomen. At the waist is an asymmetrical horizontal line likely intended to indicate the belt of this clothing, the outline of which does not survive across the sides or reverse of the figure. His left hand extends down towards the now lost lower body and likely held his erect phallus in his hand. The god likely wore a crown decorated with plumes which appears to have been slotted onto the head via a drilled hole at the forehead, though these features of the crown are now lost and the head is particularly damaged. The ears are asymmetrical in their position, with the right ear considerably higher on the side of the head than the left side. The eyes of the god are large with heavy ridges delineating the eyelids, and he has a thin nose and small shaped mouth with the lips pursed together. description.value: Head of light greyish white limestone male figure; painted. The tip of the nose is missing. Lightly chipped. Grooves and breakages, particularly around the ear on the right part of the head. Traces of red paint are visible on the cap and lips.The face is very slim and tapered. The eyes are large and rendered like added plates; the left is almond-shaped, the right lower lid is almost straight. The nose is very slim in its onset. The small mouth with the slim lips appears almost tapered because of the protruding upper lip and is smiling. The ears are very large. The helmet-like (Cypriot) cap without button-like edge is unusually high. The back is flat.

description.value: Terracotta figure of Isis-Thermuthis in a shrine.  Isis-Thermuthis, with a cobra's body and the torch of Demeter, in a shrine surmounted by a stylized cobra-frieze. She wears a schematic horn and disc crown, and a necklace with a circular pendant. The shrine is supported by a flat-fronted plinth with reliefs of the Sothic dog of Isis, and a bird, probably a Horus Falcon, flanking a simple swag.  Hollow; two-piece mould: the back is plain, with a small circular firing-vent. The underside has been smoothed, probably in modern times.  Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt, with very few traces on the front of a white dressing.
